(143, 'I have never let my schooling interfere with my education. (Mark Twain)\nSome things in life are out of your control. You can make it a party or a tragedy. (Nora Roberts)\nFind what you love and let it kill you. (Charles Bukowski)\nWhen I was a child, adults would tell me not to make things up, warning me of what would happen if I did. As far as I can tell so far, it seems to involve lots of foreign travel and not having to get up too early in the morning. (Neil Gaiman)\nAnd above all, watch with glittering eyes the whole world around you because the greatest secrets are always hidden in the most unlikely places. Those who don\'t believe in magic will never find it. (Roald Dahl)\nEveryone has talent. What\'s rare is the courage to follow it to the dark places where it leads. (Erica Jong)\nI\'ve got nothing to do today but smile. (Simon and Garfunkel)\nA diary with no drawings of me in it? Where are the torrid fantasies? The romance covers? (Cassandra Clare)\nWhen the power of love overcomes the love of power, the world will know peace. (Jimi Hendrix)\nFantasy is escapist, and that is its glory. If a soldier is imprisioned by the enemy, don\'t we consider it his duty to escape?. . .If we value the freedom of mind and soul, if we\'re partisans of liberty, then it\'s our plain duty to escape, and to take as many people with us as we can! (J.R.R. Tolkien)', '2022-07-08 21:18:40', 0),
