(572, 'He thinks he\'ll be remembered as the villain in the story. But I forgot to tell him that the villain is usually the person who locks up the maiden and throws away the key. He was the one who let me out. (Sarah J. Maas)\nEven the strongest and bravest must sometimes weep. It shows they have a great heart, one that can feel compassion for others. (Brian Jacques)\nThere are three things all wise men fear: the sea in storm, a night with no moon, and the anger of a gentle man. (Patrick Rothfuss)\nWith enough courage, you can do without a reputation. (Margaret Mitchell)\nYou\'re a painter. You\'re a baker. You like to sleep with the windows open. You never take sugar in your tea. And you always double-knot your shoelaces. (Suzanne Collins)\nMaybe our girlfriends are our soulmates and guys are just people to have fun with. (Candace Bushnell)\nWorry never robs tomorrow of its sorrow, but only saps today of its strength. (A.J. Cronin)\nToday is the sort of day where the sun only comes up to humiliate you. (Chuck Palahniuk)\nTo do the useful thing, to say the courageous thing, to contemplate the beautiful thing: that is enough for one man\'s life. (T.S. Eliot)\nIf the real world were a book, it would never find a publisher. Overlong, detailed to the point of distraction-and ultimately, without a major resolution. (Jasper Fforde)', '2022-07-08 21:18:41', 0),
